Without VPC â†’ you cannot place servers.
ğŸŸ¦ 2ï¸âƒ£ Public Subnets

These are subnets with direct internet access.

âœ” Why do we need them?

Public subnets host resources that users must access from internet, like:

Load Balancer (ALB)

Bastion Server (SSH access)

Jenkins (optional)

Frontend EC2 (if you are not using ALB)

Public subnet = internet-facing resources.
ğŸŸ§ 3ï¸âƒ£ Private Subnets

These do NOT have direct internet access.

âœ” Why do we need them?

Private subnets host internal services:

Backend EC2

RDS database

ECS containers

Internal microservices

These should NOT be reachable from internet for security.

Private subnet = secure internal servers.
ğŸŸ¨ 4ï¸âƒ£ Internet Gateway (IGW)

This allows your public subnets to access the internet.

âœ” Why do we need it?

Because without IGW:

EC2 cannot download updates (yum, apt, docker)

You cannot access EC2 via public IP

Nginx, Jenkins, or your app wonâ€™t be reachable from browser

IGW = Internet for public servers.
ğŸŸ¥ 5ï¸âƒ£ NAT Gateway (Network Address Translation)

This allows private subnet servers to access the internet WITHOUT exposing them.

âœ” Why private EC2 needs internet?

Private EC2 (backend, ECS, RDS) need internet to:

Install OS updates

Install application dependencies

Pull Docker images (ECR login)

Communicate with AWS services (SSM, CloudWatch logs)

Download build artifacts

BUT they must not have public IP â†’ security.

NAT Gateway allows:
Private EC2 â†’ NAT â†’ Internet


But internet cannot reach private EC2.

